node.text: The brown and white walls of Basilica of the Sacred Heart of Jesus in Pondicherry, India, once the sacred pilgrimage spot in India built in 1907, and elevated as a basilica in 2011. It is located just across the Pondicherry train station.

location.name: Basilica of the Sacred Heart of Jesus, Pondicherry

node.text: Police warning on the dangerous of swimming in the Bay of Bengal along Promenade Beach, Pondicherry, India. I know it’s supposed to be taken serious, but some of the warnings have a rather funny warning, like this one “Sea is for Seeing, not for Dying”, and another one “Dangerous Sea. Don’t Play with It”.
Bougainvilleas looming wildly upon the main entrance of one of the French colonial buildings on Rue Saint Louis, Pondicherry, India.
A typical street sign in Pondicherry, India which retained its name in French, with a Tamil script above.

The War Memorial overlooking the Bay of Bengal on Goubert Avenue, Pondicherry, India was inaugurated in 1971 to commemorate the French Indians who died during the World War. Notice a photobomb by a squirrel...

The imposing yellow 18th century building of the French Consulate on Rue de la Marine, Pondicherry, India. Pondicherry was administered by the French government until 1954 when it was officially returned to India.

The entrance of Lycée Français de Pondichéry, founded in 1826 as Le Collège Royal de Pondichéry is the oldest member of the French school network in the world on Rue Victor Simonel, Pondicherry, India.
Simple yet elegant settings of one of the room at Villa Helena, a heritage house with a dark-greyish blue in colour on Rue Bussy, Pondicherry, India.

Pretentiously reading a book (that I bought though, haha!) on the history of Pondicherry, India whilst enjoying a dessert at Coromandel Café & Restaurant, under the bamboo tree in the courtyard of La Maison Rose, one of converted heritage house in the city, located on Rue Romain Rolland.

Oh so French... A galette with ratatouille and mozzarella, and vanilla and coffee milkshake at the beautiful Café des Arts, on Rue Suffren, Pondicherry, India. Affectionately called as Pondy (Indianized to Puducherry these days), it is 3 to 4 hours bus ride from Chennai, and located within the Union Territory of Puducherry (a collection of four French territories up to 1954). The White Town is the French quarter - quieter, cleaner and more handsome, divided by a canal from the chaotic new town centre, the same scene you will see anywhere in India.

When in any cities that I went, I prefer to use the public transportation (rail or bus) or my two feet to roam around and discover the cities’ nook and cranny. In Chennai, I opted to use the Chennai Metro, since it is conveniently located next to the hotel that I stayed. Quite surprisingly, for a city of 8 million inhabitants, the metro system is quiet and laidback. At the moment, Chennai have only two functioning lines - Green and Blue, with the Blue Lines semi-completed (with 10 out of 17 stations functioning) which in the future will connect Chennai International Airport to the historical city centre. I had done some reading and it seems that the reason for the low ridership of the Chennai Metro since its inception in 2015 was due to the fare price which probably slightly pricey as compared to bus and suburbs train services. Some parties had deemed the metro to be a failure, but if you ask me, metros are being built for the long future run, it might be not bankable now, but soon, with the increase in population and decrease in fare, it will be of importance. This is Ekkatuthanggal Metro Station in Guindy section of Chennai, India.

These two old buildings (the YMCA Building - left & National Insurance Building - right) located on Netaji Subhash Chandra Bose Road, in the George Town area of Chennai, India, are some of the surviving architecture of the colonial era, albeit there are in an almost negligible condition. Chennai had almost 2,500 listed heritage buildings in its vicinity, second only to the city of Kolkata up north. However, like Mumbai that I went before, most of these heritage buildings are in dire need of repairs and refurbishment. If Chennai were to safe these heritage buildings, no doubt it will claim as one of the most beautiful cities in India.

Chennai (and in general India) has a collection of handsome colonial buildings, in my honest opinion, but it is hard to enjoy its beauty when too many restriction being imposed. Yes, I know it’s for their security reason, but at least trim the tree and lower bit the walls so that ordinary people could enjoy the sightings. Like this one, the Southern Railway Headquarters building, which was built in 1921 for the predecessor company of the namesake - Madras and Southern Mahratta Railway Company. It was built in Indo-Saracenic style, and almost looked like Kuala Lumpur’s Keretapi Tanah Melayu Berhad building - like its twin. This building is located just next to Chennai Central railway station on Poonamallee High Road, Chennai, India.

The crimson façade of Dr Ambedkar Goverment Law College with two handsome minarets flanking the entrance door, part of the Madras High Court complex. The most imposing building here is actually the high court building, the largest judicial building in the world after London’s, with its red Indo-Saracenic exterior, majestically looming over Chennai since its completion in 1892. Unfortunately, its ground is off limit for tourists, and you cannot get a good look of the building if you are nearby because of the perimeter walls and lush trees, too bad... You can however get a glimpse of the building if you’re walking along Rajaji Salai (Beach Road).

location.name: Dr. Ambedkar Government Law College, Chennai

node.text: Walking under the railway bridge on Rajaji Salai, Cheenai, India, near the huge Reserve Bank of India Building.

The main entrance to St Mary’s Church, English’s oldest surviving church in India, completed in 1680. It is located within Fort St George, a fort built by the British East India Company back in 1653 during the foundation of Chennai (previously known as Madras), India. Nowadays, Fort St George is home to Tamil Nadu’s Legislative Assembly and Secretariat.

A busy street outside the Thousand Light Mosque, one of the oldest and biggest mosque in India, built in 1810, and of importance place of worship for the Shia. The romantic name of the area - Thousand Lights - was said to be originated from the mosque, where in the olden days, thousand of lights (probably exaggeration) were lit up to brighten the mosque compound at night (although there’s another version which said the origins are from thousand lights that were lit during the Indian National Congress Annual Session that was held for the first time in Chennai). Can’t deny it that the name is kind of romantic though - although the area is hectic and noisy!

The entrance of the Government Museum, in Egmore, Chennai, India, a complex of buildings with the oldest being built in 1851, and it is the second oldest museum in the country. The older buildings are distinctively red in colour. It has a huge collection of artifacts and exhibition, ranging from anthropology, archeology, geology, biology and a well organized Bronze gallery (although some exhibits are very limited in information, and some areas are deteriorating).

Shunning away from the sweltering hot streets of Chennai, India into this peaceful oasis (although the vehicles’ honks can still be heard fadedly...) for a cup of cappuccino, Wild Garden Café at Amethyst, which shares it ground with a boutique and florist, located in Royapettah section of Chennai, India.

Rolls and rolls of textiles being arranged during the opening hour of Narantuul Market, better known as Black Market, Ulaanbaatar’s version of Petaling Street but on a grand scale. Here, you can have everything including furniture sets and military items, other than food, shoes, textiles, carpets and such. Black Market is located on Narnii Road, 3 kilometers southeast of the city centre.

The most prominent shopping centre (and the oldest) in Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia - State Department Store, opened in 1924, along Peace Avenue, the major artery of the city. The best thing here on the top floor where you can found all souvenirs and handicrafts from Mongolia.

The Central Museum of Mongolian Dinosaur is situated at Freedom Square, Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia but the building exterior is far from interesting. However, inside I am utterly amazed! Being a bit dinophile myself, the dinosaurs collection are impressive, especially the remains of Tarbosaurus Bataar, the cousin of America’s Tyrannosaurus Rex which had been returned to Mongolia after an unsuccessful attempt to auction the bones by a smuggler in New York City in 2012. Other than that, the exhibition included all the findings at the Gobi desert such as a nest of eggs, protoceratops, oviraptors, skull of ankylosaurus and ancient turtles! Good excursion for the kids!

Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia is probably the only city in the world where you can see a lot of Toyota Prius on its road! From my reading, 13% of the cars in the city are of Prius. One of the reason is that no environmental taxes were imposed on these type of cars as it was deemed environment friendly. As Ulaanbaatar had been voted one of the polluted city in the world due to coal burning, having Prius can relief the stress a little bit. A secondhand Prius can be sold as low as USD2500. Another quirky fact here is that, Mongolians drive on the right side of the road (most of cars then came from Russia), but as there are looking towards east nowadays - to their friends South Korea and Japan, they’re importing cars with the drivers on the right seat! It’s quite confusing and sometimes dangerous especially if they’re trying to overtake other cars on the road! Not sure whether there is a future amendment of its road rules.

Morning hike up Zaisan Hill with the Zaisan Monument built on top of the hill to  commemorate the allied Soviet and Mongolian armies who died during the World War II. Zaisan Hill is located just north of Ulaanbaatar, across the Tuul river and from up here you can see majestic panorama of the city centre.
Tsedenbal Square, located in front the red walled Mongolia’s National Academic Drama Theatre, just southwest of Sükhbaatar Square, Ulaanbaatar’s main square.

Back in the Ulaanbaatar city after 9 days in the outback and hunting for a hot coffee in the cold early autumn whether and passed by this homage to the British supergroup - The Beatles. The Beatles Square is located in front of the State Department Store and was erected in late 1990s as a tribute for 1970s Ulaanbaatar teenager during the communist era who learned and sang popular Beatles’ song in the stairwell from contraband records smuggled from Eastern Europe. Paul McCartney’s statue is barefooted here!
The beautiful Tuul River, the third longest river in Mongolia, slowly passing through Gorkhi-Terelj National Park, before flowing to the city of Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia about 50 kilometers to the west.
Cows, yaks and sheeps happily and peacefully grazing at Gorkhi-Terelj National Park, Mongolia.

Like a turtle staring towards the heaven... Turtle Rock, one of the popular sights at Gorkhi-Terelj National Park, Terelj, Mongolia, a popular weekend excursion for city dwellers. This National Park feels more Swiss than Mongolian in my humble opinion!
The preparation of Mongolian barbecue, by placing meat with onion and salt in a pressure cooker together with hot stones (chuulu) from the oven. Sometimes vodka is added!
Colourful roadside stalls en route to Gorkhi-Terelj National Park, the nearest National Park to Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia.

The current world title holder for the tallest equestrian statue in the world at 40 feet, the Chinggis Khan (Gengis Khan) statue, completed in 2010 in time with 800th anniversary of the famous Mongol Empire leader. It is located about an hour drive east of Ulaanbaatar in Tsonjin Boldog, Töv Province, Mongolia.

Unplanned stop at Khögnö Khan Uul Nature Reserves in the Bulgan Province, Mongolia to do a little hiking (one hour) through the boulder strewn valley to see the ruins of 17th century Övgön Khiid monastery, and finished it off with a climb on a huge boulder to catch this view (picture doesn’t do justice here!).

In all we have stayed in four gers (Mongolian yurts) and each is unique. At Hustai National Park, just southwest of Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia, we stayed in a ger owned by a Mongolian nomadic family, and as the temperature descended (autumn comes early in Mongolia!), we had to heat up the inside ourselves, using cowpies provided, haha! It comes free with annoying flies! Haha!

Had a one night stay at Hustai National Park, southwest of Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia to  see the takhi horses, Mongolia’s wild horses. Takhi horses were deemed extinct in the wild due to human encroachment, interbreeding with domestic horses and hunting. However, they managed to introduce back the takhi horses in the wild thanks to takhi horses that were kept in the zoo worldwide. Since the introduction in 1993, there are about 300 takhi horses in Hustai National Park alone. Takhi horses are smaller than normal horses with a distinctive stripes on their knees.

A pleasant stop at our driver’s friend’s abode at Ulaanshiveet, Mongolia for lunch. Was served with warm cow’s milk, vegetarian buuz (dumplings) and sweet milk with rice for dessert. The buuzs are superb!

After 7 hours, finally arrived in Kharkhorin, the ancient capital of Mongol Empire! The main landmark of the town is Erdene Zuu monastery, the most sacred Buddhist site in Mongolia, which is enclosed in walls of 108 stupas - a Buddhist sacred number I was told. During the Communist era, the temple inside was destroyed as any other temples in the country. This monastery is part of Orkhon Valley UNESCO World Heritage Site inscribed in 2004.

It was a long way drive through the edge of the Gobi desert to the Central Mongolian region today, with cold shower most of the time. Our driver stopped by a Mongolia nomadic family that herd sheeps and they were kind enough to have us in the yurt and served us horse’s milk. Horse’s milk taste like gorgonzola cheese! Haha!
Camping by the Ongi river today near the Ongiin Khiid monastery ruins, Dundgovi Province, Mongolia.

A blue house, a blue van and a blue sky near Ongiin Khiid monastery ruins, on the northern edge of Gobi desert, Dundgovi Province, Mongolia. The Russian made Bukhanka UAZ minivan is one of the common transportation used to ferry tourists around the Gobi desert

On our way to Orgiin Khiid, passing through long stretches of fences where zags (saxual shrub) are being planted with the cooperation from South Korea governments, within the vicinity of Bayanzag, Ömnögovi Province, Mongolia.

End of 6th day in Mongolia.

Location: Flaming Cliffs, Ömnögovi Province, Mongolia.
A race to the end of the Gobi desert, Mongolia!

Wild rhododendrons fluttering in the wind during our lunch stop in the middle of the Gobi desert, Mongolia. Interesting fact, the flowers are actually edible, and it taste like onion, and yes, I did tasted it!

Also dubbed as Duut Mankhan or Singing Sand, Khongoryn Els looks really gorgeous, but the climb on top is really strenuous with some parts are almost vertical (or maybe I’m exaggerating, haha!) hence I did not make it on top! This sand dune is huge! It is about 100 kilometers long and 12 kilometers wide. Located in the western part of Gurvan Saikhan National Park, Mongolia.

Quietly hidden on top of a hill, this petroglyphs known as The Gallery is the biggest of all rock canvas at a place known as Khavtsgait. Believed to be 8000 to 3000 BC in age, these stone carvings depicted horses, camels, ibexes, wheeled carts and goats. It is located in the vicinity of Gurvan Saikhan National Park, Mongolia.

Sweeping view of the Flaming Cliff (locally known as Bayanzag) name given by Roy Chapman Andrews who discovered fossilised dinosaurs’ bones and eggs here back in 1922. Bayanzag is located about 12 kilometers east of an oasis town called Bulgan, on the edge of Gobi desert, Mongolia.
Footprints in the sand at Khongoryn Els, Gurvan Saikhan National Park, Mongolia.

Another night in the ger due to dust and strong wind outside, well, in make sense, we are near Khongoryn Els, a 100 kilometers long sand dunes with a maximum heights of about 300 meters, remotely located in Gurvan Saikhan National Park, Mongolia. It took a good 4 hours drive across the Gobi desert to get here!
Inside the traditional Mongolian nomadic ger, and this one housed an old lady near the entrance of Khongoryn Els, a majestic sand dunes on the western side of Gurvan Saikhan National Park, Mongolia.
Morning at Gurvan Saikhan National Park, Mongolia.

At first we wanted to continue camping, however the weather tonight is so cold added by the strong wind so we ended up stayed in a ger, an equivalent of Mongolian yurt but cater for tourist. This one is located near the eastern entrance of Gurvan Saikhan National Park at Yolyn Am near Dalanzadgad, Mongolia.

Gorgeous and breathtaking on my hike to see the ice field of Yolyn Am Gorge, part of Gurvan Saikhan National Park, Mongolia. Although we did not reach the ice field (or probably the ice had already melted since it is end of summer!), the view all through the gorge is stunning!
After two days of no bath, stopped by here at a public bath house (notice the shower head in the signboard?) in the small city of Dalanzadgad, Mongolia before heading to Gurvan Saikhan National Park.

The Gobi desert is flourished with these purple and white rhododendrons, creating a colourful carpet, not what one would imagine of a desert landscape. Gobi desert is one of the coldest desert in the world, but I had a good night sleep here with clear stars in the pitch dark (and shooting stars too!).
When the camels are busy gossiping in the middle of the desert, and all you can get are their behinds! A scene near Tsogt-Ovoo, Mongolia. Just look at the flat plains behind under the cloudy sky!

No, that is not a satellite image! I’m capturing the view of the lower part of Tsagaan Suvarga from one of the cliffs with my friends down there as a scale. Can you spot them? Tsagaan Suvarga is tuck quietly in the middle of the Gobi desert, Mongolia, and it is one of the place where deafening silent terms applies!

The beautiful white cliff graced in pastel shades of orange, pink, purple and brown with patches of green at Tsagaan Suvarga, one of Mongolia’s best kept secret in the middle of Gobi desert in the Dundgovi Province, about a 160 kilometers southeast of the town of Mandalgovi.
One petrol station town, although the petrol station is out for the day in the tiny settlement of Huld, Dundgovi, Mongolia.

Granite rocks dominate this peculiar landscape at Baga Gazriin Chuluu, Dundgovi, Mongolia. Seen here during the sunrise, the terrain is not that high and worth the climb, although precaution must be taken when you stepped on the loose rocks!

Reminded me of an 80s cigarette advertisement! Camping in the green fields of Baga Gazriin Chuulu, a granite hill formation, tucked quietly about 2 hours from the main Zuunmod-Mandalgov Highway! Other than the beautiful granite formations, one can see wildlife such as horses, ibexes, eagles and gophers! And it was cold and windy last night that my tent was tilted to one side!
When you car broke down in the middle of  nowhere, try to find the beauty of the stranded place... En route to Baga Graziin Chuulu yesterday, with no internet connection back then!
No words... Somewhere along Zuunmod-Mandalgovi Highway, an hour drive outside of Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia.

My last cup of vanilla latte at Café 9 on Baga Toiruu Street, one of many cafés in Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia, before venturing out into Mongolia’s wilderness tomorrow! Can’t wait and wishing myself a bonne chance et bon courage!
After went through a horrendous traffic in the capital city of Mongolia, Ulaanbaatar, it is nice to be treated with a nice dormitory room with a tinge of traditional Mongolian decoration.

After 7 years, I’m back at Beijing Capital International Airport, Beijing, China about 35 kilometers northeast of the city centre, for a 7-hours transit for my next flight to Mongolia. So quiet at 2 in the morning!
Newly refurbished Golden Lounge at the Satellite Terminal in Kuala Lumpur International Airport, Sepang, Selangor with peranakan theme and it looks spacious!

node.text: First time here for lunch after so many pass-by at this restaurant, quietly tucked in an island surrounded by busy major roads. Tupai Tupai serves mainly Malay dishes, but popular with all Malaysians, is located off Jalan Istana in Bukit Petaling, across the MCIS Zurich building on Jalan Dewan Bahasa and is named after squirrels!

A slice of French in a crêperie in Langkawi called My French Factory on Pantai Cenang, Langkawi, Kedah. The chefs are French, so one can claimed that it is authentically French, serving crêpe bretagne, gaufre sucrée and sweet/savoury crêpes. 🥞
Bean bags and cold beer on a hot sunny beach at Kalut Bar on Tanjung Rhu beach, Langkawi, Kedah and no, I’m a teetotaller so no beer for me! #livinghealthy #yeahright #eyesrolled
Lunch amidst the paddy field in the quieter side of Pulau Langkawi, Kedah at Pia’s The Padi, just off the main Jalan Ulu Melaka in Kampung Padang Gaong.

Zoo Negara (National Zoo) located in Hulu Klang, Selangor was opened back in 1963, the year the Federation of Malaysia was formed. Over the years, human settlements had encroached the zoo’s parameters, and now it can’t expand anymore, sadly. The exhibit animals are quite awesome though, although some things needed upgrade and maintenance fast!

20 years of Kuala Lumpur International Airport and this is my first time doing plane spotting (yeah, I’m lousy like that, haha!) at Jalan Pekeliling, KLIA, Sepang, but managed to stay there less than 5 minutes due to emergency (my nephew realised that I’m not around and he dramatically cried at his house! Haha!)

From outside, it looks like a typical old Chinese wooden house in the rural area of Malaysia, but inside, it was smartly renovated with a small garden in the backyard. This is Mansion 1969 café, located quietly beside the busy Jalan Klang-Banting in Jenjarom, Selangor near the Telok Panglima Garang SKVE toll plaza.

node.text: My visit to Jakarta this time was welcomed at the new Terminal 3 of Bandara Sukarno-Hatta, Cengkareng (hence CGK), Indonesia, and I must say I’m impressed and proud! It’s about time Jakarta to follow her neighbours in providing a welcoming gateway for visitors all around the world. Although the old Terminal 2 is still impressive because of the traditional interior and exterior, Terminal 3 is much modern in style and ginormous! Hoping for a better connection from the airport to the city centre in the near future!

Morning at Bloom at Hotel Monopoli in Kemang, Jakarta, Indonesia one of Jakarta’s new accommodation addition. I was told that Kemang is the place for Jakartan youngsters to hangout, and this hotel is one of the place. The rooms are extremely nice, but light-sleepers beware, the rooftop is a party scene during the weekend nights and the loud noise can easily kill your mood, especially if you’re staying one level below the rooftop. Although earplugs are provided, the vibration can still cause you restless sleep, haha! But in all, nice hotel to stay.
Fireworks finalé as seen from outside of Gelora Bung Karno stadium, Senayan, Jakarta, Indonesia!

Congratulation Indonesia!! Extravagant and culturally awesome show for the opening ceremony of the 18th Asian Games 2018 at Stadium Gelora (shortform for Gelanggang Olahraga) Bung Karno, in Senayan, Jakarta, Indonesia! The second time this city hosting the game after 56 years!! Although I got booed, hahaha, but hey, I love Indonesia! Got a lot of friends here too! This misunderstanding have to be resolved eventually in the future! Haha! And hearing Anggun’s voice live for the first time is simply mesmerizing!
Coffee stop at Kopi Kota Tua, at the vicinity of Taman Fatahillah, in Kota Tua (Old City), Jakarta, Indonesia.

Spot the bicycle and plant! Colourful polka dots at the once all white Obliteration Room, adorned by visitors at this interactive exhibition from Yayoi Kusama, one of Japanese most recognized living artist at Museum MACAN (Modern and Contemporary Art in Nusantara) in Kebon Jerok, Jakarta, Indonesia.

node.text: Façade restoration of this old residential buiding on Jalan Rembia, Bukit Bintang, with helyconias and dragonflies on a blue backdrop. Again, I really do hope that the Kuala Lumpur City Hall will make sure it is maintain properly.
Pastel-coloured Atlantis waffle and gula melaka latte, indulgence at Shugatori Dessert Café, Damansara Utama, Selangor. Thumbs up for the taste and creativity.

node.text: Plants at the common area of Decadents by Four Seasons at Four Seasons Kuala Lumpur lower ground floor.

Endless.

Location: MRT Taman Midah, Kuala Lumpur.
The choice of colours are quite regal for these pre-war shophouses along Bussorah Street, overlooking the famous Masjid Sultan in Kampung Glam area, Singapore.

Mesmerising and calming art projection called Black Waves, inspired by the Japanese art at Singapore’s ArtScience Museum at Bayfront Avenue. Such a cool art and science museum, at totally fun for the kids as well!
Brunch at the Lokal on Neil Road, Singapore! Their coffee are good!!

Haven’t been here for a quite some time now, and surprise to see everything had been refurbished! And this IKEA Café too! This is the IPC Shopping Centre at Mutiara Damansara, a 20 minutes MRT ride from Muzium Negara MRT station.

node.text: Vibrant street art at Butterworth Art Walk in Bagan Luar, Butterworth, Penang. Honestly, Butterworth needs a rejuvenation program, in a big scale! Compared to George Town, just across the straits, Butterworth is more gritty and dilapidated, plus the town planning seems erratic. Need more attention from the authority I guess, my two cents though.
Turquoise stairs of Fuku Eatery & Desserts, tucked in a 1925 building on Lebuh Pantai (Beach Street), George Town, Penang.

node.text: Penang shophouses are basically beautiful and aesthetic in designs. Why can’t the building these days replicate them? These three-storey shophouses are loacted along Jalan Dato’ Koyah, George Town.

Fly swan fly! A Penang service ferry named after Pulau Angsa off coast of Kuala Selangor, Selangor depicting swans (angsa is swan in Malay). Up until 1985, the ferry service is the only mean of transportation to Penang Island and the mainland with the ferry terminal in Butterworth (which started in 1925). I used to remember there were a lot of ferries compared to now, but since there are two bridges linking the island and mainland, many ferries were decommissioned and if I’m not mistaken, today there are only six (6) ferries in service.

Randomly picked an eatery for a quick fix of char koay teow and milo kosong ais... Just heaven... This is Kedai Kopi Bee Hwa on Lebuh Dickens, George Town just opposite the Ibupejabat Polis Kontinjen Pulau Pinang’s entrance.

Refreshing addition to the mundane walls of Pasar Seni MRT station, a mural depicting the scene of the nearby Petaling Street by one of Malaysia’s local talent. This can be seen on the Pintu A of the station. More public art should be encouraged at all stations to make it more vibrant and have a community touch.
A cup of cappucino with a view of the oldest Hindu temple in Kuala Lumpur, the Sri Mahamariamman temple at Etc. on Jalan Tun HS Lee.
Rainbow coloured perspectives under the arches of five-foot path of pre-war shophouses along Jalan Ah Peng (after the same person Jalan San Peng in Kuala Lumpur named for) in Bentong, Pahang.
Lunching in the woods at Pinto Coffee, tranquil hideout in Janda Baik, Pahang.

A nice place to learn the history of Bentong, Pahang. The one year old Bentong Gallery, housed in the old Tong Shoon Company building, owned by the famous towkay Loke Yew. Even the main street here is named after him.

node.text: Beautiful and pristine Chamang waterfall, northwest of Bentong, Pahang.
Typical morning breakfast at one of the busiest mamak in the town of Bentong, Pahang, Tawakal Restaurant and Café on Jalan Ah Peng. A vibrant Sunday morning in this little town east of Kuala Lumpur!
Woke up to lush greenery (on-and-off) these days. Calm and tranquil. Hope that this tiny forest will not be disturbed.

One type of houses that I love in Putrajaya, the administrative capital of Malaysia. Opened in 1999, to ease the burden of Kuala Lumpur, most of the population in Putrajaya works in the government sectors. It was named in honour of the first prime minister, Tunku Abdul Rahman Putra Al-Haj. This semi-detached house in located in Precint 18, with an English vibe, and the price is ain’t cheap. Putrajaya has become one of the city in Malaysia with expensive houses, but a thing that I like it here, is that no modification is allowed on the houses façades, so the houses are quite uniformed on the exterior.

Awesome and nostalgic feel at Kluang Rail Coffee, the original pioneer, located in the original Kluang railway station. This kopitiam is so famous that it is a common thing to hear that some people drove as far as from Kuala Lumpur and Singapore for their simple breakfast of butter kaya toast, Kluang coffee and half-boiled eggs.

Another surprise (and I definitely will come back here to discover this quaint little town more!) is this secluded and tranquil town that still retained its colonial charm - Renggam, Johor. Although overshadowed by the larger Simpang Renggam, Renggam is beautiful place to see the quiet side of Malaysia which is mostly untouched by development! Hope this town stays like this for years to come! Love at first sight in Renggam, Johor.

An opportunity to discover lesser known places in Malaysia is something I’m looking forward to always! Today, I attended my nieces wedding in Simpang Renggam, Johor and I decided to bring my family on a roadtrip on the inner road of Johor, and the verdict, it is actually one of scenic route in my humble opinion with rolling hills, straight roads and oil palm plantations! Passing through the little town of Layang-Layang, Johor (either it was named after the swiflets or the kite), we stopped by at these truss bridges which accommodate the Gemas-Johor Bahru single railway track, that spanned over Sungai Sayong. Definitely built during the British colonial period, I will do some more digging on this old charm structures!
Melantak session at Indobowl SS15 Subang Jaya!! There are Indomie Ayam Goreng Jawa, Nasi Dendeng Daging, Nasi Ayam Madura and Indomie Ayam Sambal Ijo! Heaven!!!!

node.text: The beauty in the chaos of Flowers in the Window café on Jalan Dhoby, Johor Bahru, Johor. The food was excellent!

9th Syawal... In the search of burasak and lepat loi ‘tapau’. Haha! This stall is located along Jalan Pontian, Pontian, Johor near the Kayu Ara Pasong junction. Ketupat and rendang is so yesterday... Hahaha!
Italian setting at Favola, Le Meridien Kuala Lumpur at KL Sentral, Kuala Lumpur.

node.text: On cloud nine on Jalan Berangan, Bukit Bintang, Kuala Lumpur.
Elegant setting of Wurst KL on the basement level of Hotel MOV on Jalan Berangan, Kuala Lumpur with a built-in slide in case you’re super lazy to push the lift button.

node.text: May this colourful alley between Jalan Berangan and Changkat Bukit Bintang could bear the test of time and weathering in Kuala Lumpur.

If you want to feel like you’re celebrating the Eid overseas, then go to Masjid Wilayah Persekutuan on Jalan Duta, Kuala Lumpur where most of the congregation are expatriates working in Malaysia of Indian, Bangladeshi, Pakistani, African, and Middle-Easterners background. Try to find my dad in the sea of people! Anyway, it is not too late for me to wish a Happy Eid Ul-Fitr to all my family, friends and Muslim tout le monde.

Since I will be celebrating Eid-Mubarak in my hometown of Batu Caves, Selangor this year which is seriously a step away from Kuala Lumpur, why not just have a quiet time enjoying a cup of Macchiato at Botanica & Co at Alila Bangsar on Jalan Ang Seng, Brickfields. The reason being we decided to celebrate Eid in the city is that for the next two weekends, we will be in Johor. However, planning to go to Ipoh tomorrow to visit a relative there!

node.text: Last night birthday iftar at Fittie Sense in Bangsar, Kuala Lumpur, a healthy plate of roasted chicken with spinach, avocado and quinoa and a hot cup of butterfly pea (bunga telang) honey lemon. Simple but really satisfying! Last stretch of Ramadhan!

node.text: Blessed! Breaking fast and birthday treat (forced treat, haha!) here at Holiday Inn Glenmarie, Shah Alam, Selangor. Thank you my friends!
Peculiar signboard along Shangxiajiu Pedestrian Street in the old section of Guangzhou, China which cater towards the local more than the tourist.

The view of Zhujiang New Town where the tallest buildings in Guangzhou, China are located. At 530 meters, the Guangzhou CTF Finance Centre (completed in 2016) is currently the tallest office building in the city, followed by 439 meters tall Guangzhou IFC tower which is located adjacent to each other separated by the Mall of the World in the centre.
The late Zaha Hadid’s touch on Guangzhou Opera House reflected in the shallow pool opened in 2010, by the leftbank of Pearl River, Guangzhou, China.
Public art of Guangzhou Tram station, colourful glass adorning the Liede Bridge South station.

One of the unique colonial buildings with a protruding balcony on top of the entrance that was built in 1924 to house the Administration Bureau of Broadcasting and Nationalist Government on Shamian Island, Guangzhou, China.
One of the colonial buildings that once housed the Indian nationals in Shamian Island, Guangzhou, China.

The lush green grounds of Starbucks Reserve on Shamian Island, Guangzhou, China, housed in one of the colonial buildings with seafoam exterior. I guess we need this kind of giant corporation to save and reuse old buildings.

Guangzhou, China has a sizeable Muslim community so it is actually easy to get Halal food here. Just head to Xiaobei metro station and you can find lines of Turkish, Middle East and Hadramawt restaurants. These restaurants open till late during the holy month of Ramadhan.

Peppered with bronze statues, and lined with a huge parks in the middle, Shamian Island is a former concession area owned by the English and French at the end of the Opium War before being returned to the Chinese government in 1946. The buildings here are of British and French designed and you can easily differentiate them. Shamian Island is originally a kilometer long sandbanks.

Perched on top of a small hill within Yuexiu Park on the northwest side of Guangzhou, China is the Five Goats Statue - the pride symbol of the city. With the height of 11 meters and made of solid granite, it was built in 1959 collaborated by three famous Chinese sculptors, and represents a 2000 years old legend, when Guangzhou was a small agricultural village with famine, and came five goddesses riding enchanted goats descending from the heaven to help the villagers.

node.text: The new Guangzhou Library built in 2013, located in the Pearl River (Zhujiang) New Town. At an angle, the building looks like stack of books which suited the building purpose.

Canton Tower with rainbow coloured lights swirling around the structure is located on the right bank of Zhujiang (Pearl River), this one viewed from the southern section of the Mall of the World, a beautiful huge square with underground mall, jogging tracks and artificial eco-forest. At a glance, Guangzhou, dubbed the Los Angeles of China, at this time of year feels like Singapore (the weather and the ambience). It is the third largest city in China and I’m super surprise because it is super clean and efficient, at par with Shanghai! Since it is Ramadhan, so I will fix the good time to explore the city since it is quite hot and humid in the day. Ending my May and starting my June here in this city, and enjoy while it last!
The long corridor of Masjid Negara (National Mosque) in Kuala Lumpur connected to Makam Pahlawan (Warriors’ Mausoleum).
Throwback to early May at the beautiful Moti Mahal or Pearl Palace, one of the palace located inside Mehrangarh Fort in Jodhpur, India.

node.text: Flowery door of Hawa Mahal, the Palace of Wind in Jaipur, India built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh.

It is not REALLY OLD (Maha Lama), but this signboard on an apothecary in Pekan Melayu, Alor Setar, Kedah indicates that it used to be the located of the old Maha Klinik, owned by our current Prime Minister, Tun Dr Mahathir Mohamad. The current Maha Klinik is located on Jalan Tunku Ibrahim, some hundreds meters away for the original location.
Beauty when the nature took over the abandoned shophouses in Pekan Melayu, Alor Setar, Kedah.
A very calm Friday, a week before the beginning of Ramadhan, and the new beginning of Malaysia as a whole. Friday prayer at Masjid Raja Haji Fisabilillah, Cyberjaya, Selangor.

Let’s just say this is my celebratory treat for a new Malaysia, haha! Having a small retreat while waiting for my parents celebrating the success with their friends at this cozy café in Taman Melawati, Selangor called Playground Coffeery.

9th May 2018, the date where Malaysians choose the government for the 14th time. An early morning scene on the election day at Kampung Klang Gate with the scenic quartz ridge as the backdrop. Today, it is either #lainkalilah or #inikalilah.

location.name: Tanah Perkuburan Islam Kampong Klang Gate Baru

node.text:
My imperfect great leader. Sure, you’re just human. You made mistakes. You have been praised and you have been condemned. The haters can say whatever they want, but for me, thanks to you, Malaysia is known throughout the world, and the outside world really admire you, although in your own country, you were non stopped criticized. Alas, again, at 93 years old, you stepped up to save the country from mismanagement of the government. We shall see whether money or integrity wins. And it starts tomorrow. Win or lose, I will always admire you, my imperfect great leader.

Location: Mahathir’s Mural on Lorong Setar, Alor Setar, Kedah.

That café in the middle of nowhere. Ink Library Café at Eco Grandeur, Persiaran Mokhtar Dahari, Puncak Alam, Selangor. Persiaran Mokhtar Dahari connects Subang to Batu Arang and was named after one of the greatest Malaysia footballer, the late Mokhtar Dahari.

node.text: I supposed to join the 10km Perlis Marathon today, but I totally forgot about it in favour to the General Election hype. I had even bought a flight ticket and totally forgotten about it until I was reminded by the apps, hahaha! So, here I am in the end, spending my Saturday discovering the city where I was born, and stopped by this rustic conserved heritage building - an old prison I was informed (hence the name of the main street it fronting on the side) - called Caffe Diem, with an old Perahu Kedah dangling on the ceiling. It is located in Pekan Cina (at the corner of Jalan Tunku Yaacob and Jalan Penjara Lama), Alor Setar, Kedah, and had received several famous customers from the Sultan and Sultanah of Kedah to Tun Dr Mahathir Mohamad and his family.

node.text: Effingly gorgeous!! Oops, sorry for the language but this is absolutely beautiful! Located near the airport, in the new city of Jaipur, on the grounds of Jawahar Circle, the largest circle with garden in India, is this beautiful gate called Patrika Gate. It is not historical and definitely new, built less than five years ago, but the Rajasthani art showed here is splendidly brilliant! Thanks to my taxi driver for awesomely stopped just for the sake of me taking this photo!

Vendors and a passenger passing by the train on Platform 4, Jodhpur Junction train station. Amazingly enough, the train station is really clean, a stark difference once you step onto the city street. And that’s the reason India is amusing, it’s full of surprises!
Local boys cooling off at Toorji Ka Jhalra (Toorji’s Step Well) in Jodhpur, India.
Narrow streets of the old quarter of Jodhpur, India. 💙💙💙
The reward for that grueling 9 hours bus ride yesterday! A very large and cozy room at Pal Haveli, Jodhpur, India, a two centuries mansion north of Sardar Market, the main market of the city.
Palki Café at the entrance of Mehrangarh Fort, Jodhpur, India on a hot spring day.

node.text: The most beautiful room in all Mehrangarh Fort, the Phool Mahal or the Flower Palace, with golden filigree and colourful walls and ceiling. Mehrangarh means ‘death’ and this fort dominates the skyline of Jodhpur, India.  Interestingly enough, there are vultures circling over the fort at any given them, and they’re usually associated with death! Creepy!

node.text: If Léa Seydoux visits this city, she might agree that blue is the warmest colour. One of the houses with tint of blue on its exterior wall in the old quarter of Jodhpur, India. The blue colour is said to cool off the house as Jodhpur received a very hot temperature on daily basis. In India, it is known as the sun city, and I have to agree, as it is really hot here and I was drenched in sweat after only few hours.

From the Pink City of Jaipur to the Blue City of Jodhpur. Stark contrast to the barren land of the Thar Desert, the houses of old city of Jodhpur are painted in variety hues of blue. Sea of azure, aquamarine, indigo, turquoise, cerulean can be seen clearly up above the Mehrangarh Fort, perched on top of a rocky hill that dominates the old part of the city.
Stopping for a masala chai in the blue city of Jodhpur, India.
